[[File:Farrah Fawcett 1977.JPG|thumb|[[Farrah Fawcett]], from the 1970s series ''[[Charlie's Angels]]'']] '''Jiggle television''' is a term coined by [[NBC]] executive [[least objectionable program|Paul Klein]] to criticize [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s television production and marketing strategy under [[Fred Silverman]].<ref name="Jezierski" /> Klein referred to ABC's programs as "[[pornography|porn]]" in order to tap into the 1970s [[moral panic]] and anxiety over the spread of pornography,<ref name="Semonche" /> using the [[neologism]] to describe the use of female television celebrities moving in loose clothing or [[underwear]] in a way in which their [[breast]]s or [[buttocks]] could be seen to move, or "jiggle."<ref name="fifty">{{cite book |title=Fifty Years Among the New Words: A Dictionary of Neologisms, 1941–1991 |first=John |last=Algeo |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=1993 }}</ref> An American invention,<ref name="point" /> it was used to refer to programs such as ''[[Charlie's Angels]]'',<ref>{{cite book |title=Violent Femmes: Women As Spies in Popular Culture |first=Rosie |last=White |publisher=Taylor & Francis |year=2007 }}</ref> ''[[Wonder Woman (TV series)|Wonder Woman]]'' and ''[[Three's Company]]'',<ref name="Semonche">Censoring Sex: A Historical Journey Through American Media. John E. Semonche, Rowman & Littlefield, 15 Aug 2007</ref> which used the sexuality of young women as appeal to their audiences.<ref>Wallowing in Sex: The New Sexual Culture of 1970s American television. Elana Levine. Duke University Press, 19 Dec 2006</ref> The program's plots were often sexist, full of innuendo and suggestive language, and unrealistic in nature.<ref>Perspectives on Radio and Television: Telecommunication in the United States. F. Leslie Smith, John W. Wright (II.), David H. Ostroff. Routledge, 1 Aug 1998</ref> Producers of such series would make sure that its lead female actors would appear in a bikini, bathing suit, négligée, underwear, or naked under a towel, in each show.<ref>Female Action Heroes: A Guide to Women in Comics, Video Games, Film, and Television. Gladys L. Knight. ABC-CLIO, 8 Jun 2010</ref>
At the time, the ABC target audience was 18 to 35 years old.<ref>Programming for TV, Radio, and the Internet: Strategy, Development, and Evaluation. Philippe Perebinossoff, Brian Gross, Lynne S. Gross. Elsevier, 24 Feb 2005</ref> Jiggle was also called "[[Breast|Tits]] & [[Buttocks|Ass]] Television" or "T&A" for short <ref>The Gatekeeper: My Thirty Years as TV Censor. Alfred R. Schneider, Kaye Pullen. Syracuse University Press, 1 May 2001</ref> and in the 1970s the amount of sex on television increased, as did its ratings,<ref name="Semonche" /> creating social controversies and consequences.<ref>Condom Nation: The U.S. Government's Sex Education Campaign from World War I to the Internet. Alexandra M. Lord. JHU Press, 23 Nov 2009</ref>
The term was later taken to new extremes by the late 1980s and throughout the 1990s and early 2000s on such television shows as ''[[Baywatch]]'', ''[[She Spies]]'', and numerous [[USA Network]] series.
==Jiggle television series== The term has been used to describe the dramatic television series of [[Aaron Spelling]] such as ''[[Honey West (TV series)|Honey West]]'', ''[[The Love Boat]]'', ''[[Fantasy Island]]'', ''[[Beverly Hills 90210]]'', ''[[Melrose Place]]'', ''[[Charmed]]'' and others.<ref>Jiggle Tv: Charlie's Angels and Aaron Spelling's Television Legacy. Courtney Hutton. BiblioBazaar, 2010. {{ISBN|1240062885}}.</ref> Jiggle TV is seen as trashy and escapist entertainment.<ref name="Jezierski">Television Everywhere: How Hollywood Can Take Back the Internet and Turn Digital Dimes Into Dollars. Andrei Jezierski. i2 Partners LLC, 12 Oct 2010</ref> Programs or female performers are often judged by their "jiggle factor"<ref>America's Favorite Radio Station: Wkrp in Cincinnati. Michael B. Kassel. Popular Press, 15 Jun 1993</ref> and many, such as [[Pamela Anderson]] <ref name="point">Points of View. Rex Murphy. McClelland & Stewart, 23 Sep 2003</ref> had their bodies surgically modified to increase it. The term Jiggle-o is used to describe a character which uses jiggle factor and "jiggle syndrome" is used to discuss the phenomenon as a whole.<ref name="fifty" />
{{quote|When the show was number three, I figured it was our acting. When it got to be number one, I decided it could only be because none of us wears a bra.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/charlies-timeless-angels-women-who-transformed-television-413911.html |title=Charlie's timeless angels: Women who transformed television |publisher=Independent.co.uk |date=2006-08-30 |accessdate=2010-11-11}}</ref>|[[Farrah Fawcett-Majors]] on ''[[Charlie's Angels]]''}}
List of some Jiggle TV shows:{{Citation needed|date=September 2018}}
''Battle of the Network Stars'', ''Baywatch'', ''Charlie's Angels'', ''Dukes of Hazzard'', ''Fantasy Island'', ''Hee Haw Honeys'', ''[[I Dream of Jeannie]]'', ''Logan's Run'', ''The Love Boat'', ''North Shore'', ''Rowan and Martin's Laugh-In'', ''Sugar Time!'' ''Three's Company'', ''We Got It Made'', ''[[WKRP in Cincinnati]]'', ''Wonder Woman'', ''Xena: Warrior Princess''.
